overall_summary: ElizaOS Cloud officially launched and immediately saw community agent-building activity, alongside active engineering work on streaming, workflows, and authentication improvements. In parallel, Discord discussions centered on token price drawdown and lingering friction from the AI16Z→ElizaOS migration, including exchange-related concerns and requests for clearer token utility documentation.
key_facts: ElizaOS Cloud officially launched on 2025-12-26 and allows users to build and deploy AI agents.
The ElizaOS token was described in Discord as being down 90–98% from its all-time high.
A community member reported that the top 10 token holders decreased from 89% to 64% of total supply.
ElizaOS Cloud file uploads have a stated 50MB limit.
Custom model hosting in ElizaOS Cloud was stated as being on the roadmap and expected to be ready “next week.”
The migration tool only allows migration of tokens held at the November 11 snapshot, and only from the wallet that held them at that time.
Chainlink CCIP was cited as requiring the ElizaOS token to be mintable for cross-chain functionality.
Cloud revenue (but not yield) was stated to be used for ElizaOS token buybacks.
Two pull requests were opened in elizaOS/eliza on Dec 26–27, 2025 (0 merged, 0 new issues, 2 active contributors).
In Discord, a user asking whether npm can be used instead of bun was told to continue using bun.
open_questions: Is Jeju network's token going to be $elizaos?
How do I get the right role for the #1415627400456437831 channel?

twitter_news_highlights.claim: Multiple Twitter posts were noted as highlighting new projects being built on ElizaOS Cloud after launch.
A team member (CJ) gave a shoutout to a third-party project named “Aiko” built on ElizaOS Cloud.

new_issues_prs.title: Enhance multi-step workflow with retry logic and parameter extraction capabilities
new_issues_prs.author: wtfsayo
new_issues_prs.significance: Adds retry logic and parameter extraction for multi-step workflows.

new_issues_prs.title: Standardize naming conventions for message server routes
new_issues_prs.author: standujar
new_issues_prs.significance: Standardizes server route naming and is associated with cleanup and test additions referenced in core-dev discussion.

overall_focus.claim: Engineering discussions and summaries emphasized platform quality work: route standardization, streaming fixes, workflow reliability (retries), and improving authentication UX via SSO/JWT approaches.

discord_updates.summary: Discussion focused on the project’s transition from AI16Z meme coin roots to utility, token drawdown (90–98% from ATH), migration friction (snapshot-based eligibility and exchange confusion), and the importance of regaining the project’s X account for marketing. Users also shared early ElizaCloud agent examples and reported login/application errors.

Developers discussed Cloud/agent technical issues (deployment username-null error, file uploads, Ollama model configuration) and tooling constraints (bun required; npm not supported). A workaround for DaVinci Resolve assistance via Gemini screenshare was suggested.

Jeju Network questions centered on decentralization goals (confirmed as core) and an unanswered question on whether Jeju’s token will be $elizaos; a previously mentioned “life-changing event” expected around October was described as still pending with dependencies on others.
Core-dev chat referenced implementing a custom SSO to unify identity, plus PRs aimed at fixing broken streaming (wrong core dependencies) and improving code quality/tests.

user_feedback.feedback_summary: Users requested clearer public documentation for token utility/value accrual and better exchange guidance during migrations.
Multiple users reported large token losses (commonly 90–95%+) and questioned how Cloud success translates into token value.
Users reported ElizaCloud problems including login/application errors and an agent deployment issue showing a username-null error.
Feature/process requests included a structured build showcase for ElizaCloud projects and expanding marketing presence (e.g., Instagram).
Developers asked for file upload improvements (multiple markdown files, optimization) and custom model hosting support in Cloud.

strategic_insights.theme: Cloud launch traction vs. onboarding reliability
strategic_insights.insight: ElizaOS Cloud launch drove immediate community experimentation and third-party projects, but onboarding friction surfaced (login/application errors, deployment errors) alongside discussions of unifying auth via SSO.
implications_or_questions: Should SSO/auth unification be prioritized to reduce first-run failures during the launch window?
What minimum set of Cloud reliability metrics should be reported publicly to support adoption?

strategic_insights.theme: Token narrative and migration support load
strategic_insights.insight: Discord activity shows persistent migration-related confusion (snapshot constraints, exchange handling) and repeated requests for token utility clarity, occurring alongside substantial token drawdown discussions.
implications_or_questions: Is there a single authoritative migration/exchange playbook that can be published outside Discord?
What concise token-utility statement can be paired with Cloud milestones to reduce repeated questions?

market_analysis.observation: Community discussion cited the ElizaOS token as down 90–98% from ATH, with holders reporting losses of 90–95%+.
market_analysis.relevance: Sustained drawdown and holder losses dominated community conversation and shaped requests for clearer token utility.

market_analysis.observation: Concerns were raised about potential delisting from Korean exchanges (Bithumb, Coinone, Korbit) in January.
market_analysis.relevance: Potential delisting risk could affect liquidity and access for a key regional market.

market_analysis.observation: A comparison was discussed citing ElizaOS at ~22M FDV versus competitors Pippin (~536M) and Virtuals (~693M).
market_analysis.relevance: Competitor valuation comparisons influenced expectations and debate about positioning and narrative catalysts.

market_analysis.observation: Token holding concentration was reported as shifting, with top 10 holders decreasing from 89% to 64% of supply.
market_analysis.relevance: Changes in concentration were cited in the context of migration and whale activity discussions.
